{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}

An '''ethnolinguistic group''' (or '''ethno-linguistic group''') is a group that is unified by both a common [[ethnicity]] and [[language]]. Most ethnic groups have their [[First language|own language]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7oAUeUVtc58C&pg=PA12&dq=ethnic+group+language&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF2971lt_WAhWQh7QKHYnEAQcQ6AEIOjAE#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20group%20language&f=false|title=Handbook of Language and Ethnic Identity|last=Fishman|first=Joshua A.|last2=García|first2=Ofelia|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195374926|location=|pages=12|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=x3gAB7A6-bgC&pg=PA244&dq=ethnic+group+own+language&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjw3tSFl9_WAhXJI1AKHVTVAswQ6AEIWjAJ#v=onepage&q=ethnic%20group%20own%20language&f=false|title=Perspectives on Ethnicity|last=Holloman|first=Regina E.|last2=Arutiunov|first2=Serghei A.|date=1978-01-01|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=9783110807707|location=|pages=244|language=en}}</ref> Despite this, the term is often used to emphasise when language is a major basis for the ethnic group, especially with regards to its neighbours.<ref name=":0" />

A central concept in the linguistic study of ethnolinguistic groups is ethnolinguistic vitality, the ability of the group's language and ethnicity to sustain.<ref name="vitality">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Bourhis |first1=R.Y. |last2=Barrette |first2=G.|title=Ethnolinguistic Vitality |work=Encyclopedia of Language & Linguistics |year=2006 |pages=246–249 }}</ref> An ethnolinguistic group that lacks such vitality is unlikely to survive as a distinct entity. Factors that influence the ethnolinguistic vitality are demographics, institutional control and status (including language planning factors).<ref name="questionnaire">{{cite journal |last1=Bourhis |first1=R. Y.|last2=Giles |first2=H. |last3=Rosenthal |first3=D. |title=Notes on the construction of a ‘subjective vitality questionnaire’ for ethnolinguistic groups |journal=Journal of Multilingual and Multicultural Development |date=1981 |volume=2 |issue= 2|pages=145–155 |doi=10.1080/01434632.1981.9994047 }}</ref>

