[[Image:Smokingkills.jpg|thumb|right|Warning label on a cigarette box, which reportedly boosted sales of [[cigarette case]]s in the EU in 2003]] [[Image:Air bag warning sign.jpg|thumb|right|Warning label for an [[airbag]]]] [[File:Personal watercraft warning sticker.jpg|thumb|right|Warning label for a [[personal water craft]]]]
A '''warning label''' is a [[label]] attached to an item, or contained in an item's instruction manual, warning the user about [[risk]]s associated with the use of the item, and may include restrictions by the manufacturer or seller on certain uses.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Wogalter, Michael S.|year=2006|chapter=Introduction|editor=Wogalter, Michael S.|title=Handbook of warnings|location=Mahwah, New Jesey|publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum Associates|isbn=978-0-8058-4724-6}}</ref> Most of them are placed to limit civil liability in [[lawsuit]]s against the item's manufacturer or seller.<ref>{{Cite book|author1=Egilman, D. |author2=Bohme, S. R. |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2006|chapter=Purposes and Scope of Warnings|editor=Wogalter, Michael S.|title=Handbook of warnings|location=Mahwah, New Jesey|publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum Associates|isbn=978-0-8058-4724-6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=Khoury, Clarke E.|year=1989|title=Warning Labels May Be Hazardous to Your Health: Common-Law and Statutory Responses to Alcoholic Beverage Manufacturers' Duty to Warn|journal=Cornell Law Review|volume=75|pages=158–188}}</ref> That sometimes results in labels which for some people seem to state the obvious.
==Government regulation== In the United States warning labels were instituted under the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of 1938.<ref>Federal Food, Drug, & Cosmetic Act, Pub. L. No. 75-717, 52 Stat. 1040 (1938) (codified as amended at 21 U.S.C. §§ 301-99 (2006))</ref> Cigarettes were not required to have warning labels in the United States until in 1965 Congress passed the Federal Cigarette Labeling and Advertising Act (FCLAA).<ref>Federal Cigarette Labeling and Advertising Act, Pub. L. No. 89-92, 79 Stat. 282 (1965) (codified as amended at 15 U.S.C. §§ 1331-40 (1970)).</ref>
==Abnormal warning labels== Warning labels have been produced for different items. In some cases, these labels warn against some very strange occurrences such as the legendary microwave warning that states 'do not dry pets in microwave'.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Microwaved Pet|publisher=Snopes|url=http://www.snopes.com/horrors/techno/microwavedpet.asp}}</ref>
Some companies hold 'strange warning label competitions' such as the former M-law<ref>{{Cite web|title=M-Law Announces Winners Of Seventh Annual Wacky Warning Label Contest|year=2004|url=http://www.mlaw.org/wwl/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040609013049/http://www.mlaw.org/wwl/|archivedate=9 June 2004|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title="Danger: Avoid Death" Warning Wins Top Prize In M-Law's Eleventh Annual Wacky Warning Label Contest|year=2011|url=http://www.mlaw.org/wwl/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130424225408/http://www.mlaw.org/wwl/|archivedate=24 April 2013|deadurl=yes}}</ref> wacky warning labels competition.<ref>{{Cite web|author1=Nelson, Brett |author2=Finneran, Katy |lastauthoramp=yes |date=23 February 2011|title=Dumbest Warning Labels|publisher=Forbes|url=https://www.forbes.com/2011/02/23/dumbest-warning-labels-entrepreneurs-sales-marketing-warning-labels.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225220804/http://www.forbes.com/2011/02/23/dumbest-warning-labels-entrepreneurs-sales-marketing-warning-labels.html|archivedate=25 February 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref>
While many products intended for human consumption may require warning labels due to the health risks associated with using them, it is only tobacco products that have strongly worded warnings on their health risks.
